{"format": "tiptap/v1", "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T17:46:43.987Z", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Refusals and fallbacks define "}, {"type": "text", "text": "graceful degradation", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}]}, {"type": "text", "text": " when agents cannot comply — safety refusals, capability limits, tool outages — preserving user trust and system stability."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What it is"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "A refusal explains why the agent won't act. A fallback offers a partial alternative (cached data, human handoff, simplified answer). Both should be structured for UI rendering."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why it matters"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Agents that hallucinate through failures cause more damage than agents that stop clearly. Production systems route refusals to humans or alternate paths."}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "json"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\"status\": \"refused\", \"reason\": \"policy\", \"user_message\": \"...\", \"fallback\": \"contact_support\"}"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key takeaways"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Structured refusals enable routing"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Offer safe fallbacks when possible"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Never fake success on tool failure"}]}]}]}]}}